  "texts": [
    "Consequently, the continuous transition between the Z ± q ordered phases, obtained by condensing these domain walls, simultaneously destroys the Z + q order but produces the Z - q order.In this supplemental material, we provide technical details on the classical Monte Carlo (CMC) simulations and the corner transfer matrix renormalization group (CTMRG) method.",
    "Additionally, we present supplementary results from CMC and CTMRG simulations, including the characterizations of the first-order phase transitions, to further support and complement the results discussed in the main text.",
    "Deatils on the classical Monte Carlo simulationsWe employ classical Monte Carlo (CMC) simulations [1,2] to investigate different phases of the twodimensional (2D) J 1 -J 2 clock model, focusing on the J 2 /J 1 > 1/2 regime.",
    "As discussed in the main text, frustration from competing interactions limits CMC updates to single-spin Metropolis flips, rendering the method inefficient for large system sizes, particularly in critical phases.",
    "Nonetheless, deep within each phase, CMC remains a valuable tool for the identification and characterization of different phases.Here, we use 5 × 10 5 equilibration steps and 5 × 10 4 measurement steps for CMC, considering over 20 to 80 independent initial realizations."
